<!-- 6[1~4] =3D [6~24] -->=20
<p>So <span class=3D"large">Av =3D =CE=BBv</span>, and we have success!</p>=
=20
</div>=20

<p>Now it is <b>your turn</b> to find the eigenvector for the other eigenva=
lue of <span class=3D"larger">=E2=88=927</span></p>=20


<h2>Why?</h2>=20

<p>What is the purpose of these?</p>=20
<p>One of the cool things is we can use <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.c=
om/algebra/matrix-introduction.html">matrices</a> to do <a href=3D"https://=
www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/matrix-transform.html">transformations</a> in sp=
ace, which is used a lot in  computer graphics.</p>=20
<p>In that case the eigenvector is "the direction that doesn't change direc=
tion" !</p>=20
<p>And the eigenvalue is the scale of the stretch:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li><b>1</b> means no change,</li>=20
	<li><b>2</b> means doubling in length,</li>=20
	<li><b>=E2=88=921</b> means pointing backwards along the eigenvector's dir=
ection</li>=20
	<li>etc</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>There are also many applications in physics, etc.</p>=20


<h2>Why "Eigen"</h2>=20

<div class=3D"words">=20
<p>Eigen is a German word meaning "own" or "typical"</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><i>"das ist ihnen <b>eigen</b>"</i> is  German for <i>"=
that is <b>typical</b> of them"</i></p>=20
</div>=20

<p>Sometimes in English we use the word "characteristic", so an eigenvector=
 can be called a "characteristic vector".</p>=20


<h2>Not Just Two Dimensions</h2>=20

<p>Eigenvectors work perfectly well in 3 and higher dimensions.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<div class=3D"h3">Example: find the eigenvalues for this 3x3 matrix:=20
